IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Spaceflight
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It wasn’t until 1924 that it took over the name IBM – originally a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM company was the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1980s and 19th century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous card clocks for registering the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also held the chairmanship of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the boss of Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader then even overshadowed IBM’s founders – based on Watson’s ideas to this day, the company’s invincible culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name implies, began manufacturing and distributing all kinds of machines for the trade – from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson led the company, he doubled its revenues to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chief chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM's technicians and computers helped guide NASA's flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous human flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that defined the computer standard of that time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, on the other hand, it purchased the consulting part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the concept of “Smarter Planet”.
It embodies the intention to use technologies in a wise way in areas not even planned so far, for example to improve the situation in transport and city administration.
In the commercial sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smarter Commerce” platform, which is designed to help traders guide the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
Already in 1932, IBM founded a branch in then Czechoslovakia – the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno, among other things.
The Central and Eastern Europe Headquarters is based in Prague and there is also a top team of world-class researchers working on voice recognition technology.
