Travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five state-approved travel agencies in the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at the time mainly sold only trips to the socialist countries of the Eastern bloc, in the West at the time only chosen ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (German Democratic Republic - GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula by the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovakia) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter to do so, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Already then the travel agencies also offered trips to the west, but then you had to take huge queues or even sleep in your sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even that was not the case.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge - the condition for an exit to the West - was only granted to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange pledge.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays inland, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dads - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox that we are not aware of today is the fact that we could not travel to the most popular holiday country in the Czech Republic until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
From the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation in the neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, which prompted a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovakia simply could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
The Czech holidaymakers slept in the park while traveling to Paris, because who would have had the money to stay in a hotel or in a guesthouse at the time.
A typical feature of traveling abroad from the Czech Republic was a luggage compartment packed with canned food, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thus also the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare for charter flights after 1997, making air travel incredibly cheaper compared to the past thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, already had currencyless payment transactions with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-complete" travel was in 2000 when, thanks to high demand, the first direct charter flight was made to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter planes with Czech passengers fly to distant sunny countries every year; this year they fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another important moment in the era that marked our “post-revolutionary” development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita on a single holiday including the cost of the resort.
