Europe's most beautiful pools
Jump into the blue
by Julia Stanek
Ufo-optic paddling pools, splendid pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience its blue wonder - and after a city tour or a hike, rest your tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where wellness in the water is most beautiful.
If Iris Meder went on a research trip in the past one and a half years, one thing was not to be missing in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Leaning back on the water, she looked up in artfully designed domes, she swam against marble puddles waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming pools.
She liked a bath, she took it in her notebook on the fly - with interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools have been explored by architectural historian Meder in this way - and now presents them in her newly published book "Badenfreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn’t have much to do with sports, Meder says – only in the water is it different.
Annoyingly, only that swimming fans have to settle down with blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can inhale the tantalizing scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful bird whistle in the park.
"One day I wondered why swimming pools always have to be so ugly," says the Vienna-based Meder.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Platchers in the jumping pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all the senses are served, according to Meder.
And when the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real eye treat: "Instead of a floor you have a water surface in baths."
"It is transparent on the one hand, but on the other hand reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything is doubled visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, jumpboards.
The small-format picture book "Badefreude" conveys on 190 pages valuable knowledge about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
Remarkable specimens were discovered by pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in a quaint karst cave (cave in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath whose basins are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürd).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: While you have the whole city in mind from the Zurich rooftop pool, you can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam room there is a window from which you can observe the bustle on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a ufo just landed in the Alps.
From three bowls open up it steams in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool, the pool collector Meder got the smell of chlorine into his nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, in the <0xC3><0x81>rpád bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba it smells so strongly of heating oil that you hardly believe landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen carbonate-containing healing water, which is almost black and whose slick sticks to your skin as soon as you slip into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech bath Luhatchowitz, she found a locked terrain.
The bathroom designed by the architect Du<0xC5><0xA1>an Jurkovic in 1902 has now been closed.
As Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds grow between the tiles.
On the other hand, the decay has been countered in an enchanting swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of construction have already been completed; you can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements dating from the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since the meticulous modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite swimming pool of the pool-kienner Iris Meder - and not only because it originally comes from the Black Forest.
"It's already an achievement to merge such different building styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace, the diving in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor thing.
