The building was not suitable, however, either spatially or technically as a museum - no walls to hang over art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has come down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21st House" and will be used in the future as a museum of contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the Museum Belvedere, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a chance in every way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, has been enforced.
Husslein-Arco, a doctorate art historian with a considerable career, among other things, in youth as an ice skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, emphatically carried out the conversion with politicians and monument protectors, she secured the public funds and private sponsorship funds and
Apart from present-day art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookshop, and an office house had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was then the ideal cast for the execution.
Not only because he sensitively converted and expanded Joseph Olbrich’s Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but also because he studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology and the pavilion was an “extremely important place” for him, where he had viewed the exhibitions “almost every weekend”.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and ease upon its transfer to Vienna and its conversion.
There were far greater problems with the current renovation: the building was "an energy shooter," Krischanitz says.
The window profiles of the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were replaced, glass fiber reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel supports have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two basements made room for the new use, a lowered light ditch between the house and the road ensures exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the lightweight Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house has been painted in the old red-brown anti-rust shade.
The cinema is exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often, a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the Office for the Conservation of Monuments," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rubble floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and lightweight.
