And on the other hand, it had advanced as an investment bank into the league of the largest banks in the world.
That made an impression.
The former banker and later long-time banking professor in Zurich, Hans Geiger, says: "My students at the time, I always presented the UBS as a model of a good bank."
“From today’s point of view, you ask yourself: How could I be so wrong?”
He was very wrong.
In 2007, it was revealed for the first time that something was wrong in the UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli surprisingly resigned, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and equally ingenious banker.
A few months later, he knew why he had left.
The bank’s investment division had messed with subprime papers and had to write off billions.
In order to shoulder this, the UBS announced a capital increase of 13 billion francs.
For this, she actually found investors, but ones that some would have been buzzing about until shortly before: a non-transparent Asian state fund from Singapore and an Arab state fund that was so concealed that one did not even know its name.
But that was only the first blow.
In April 2008, things got worse.
The bank had to announce new billions of losses, with the resignation of Chairman of the Board of Directors Marcel Ospel, Switzerland’s second highest-paid Board of Directors in 2006.
In October 2008, the catastrophe followed: UBS faced a collapse in the face of its poor investments in the financial crisis and had to be saved by the state.
The National Bank bought UBS for tens of billions of troubled securities, while the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a forced-walled bond, through which it could become co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked - because it noticed how dramatic it is for a small country to house such large banks.
Finally, UBS’s balance sheet total in 2007 was more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see chart).
"Once again, we could not save the UBS," says banking researcher Geiger.
The first disaster followed the second.
A few months later, UBS surrendered in tax dispute with America and agreed to release the data of wealthy customers who may have misled taxes with the help of the bank.
In addition, she agreed to a payment of $780 million - in return for unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty.
The UBS thus acknowledged more or less openly that it had helped with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in competition for rich customers: the nimbus of secrecy.
After the scandal, the Swiss banking secret was no longer the same.
The resignation of the Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the Board of Directors followed.
And the exodus of customer money.
Thus, within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both core business areas: in investment banking due to misspeculation and in asset management due to tax evasion assistance.
And just as it got a little quieter again, just as you thought UBS would get it back, this unfortunate trader story follows: A single trader loses 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is wrong.
And it becomes apparent: with risk management in investment banking it is obviously still not working.
"With the case of Adoboli, it has been determined that risk control has changed too little," says Martin Janssen, economist and finance professor at the banking institute of the University of Zurich.
The chief financial officer of a large German bank is also certain: "The problem with UBS is that it does not have the risk control under control."
It was precisely the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago assumed to become guardians of the great fortunes of the world: no too great risks, but security for the money - even beyond the Alpine Republic could once collapse the world.
The vaults of Swiss banks had become a symbol of unwavering reliability like Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly noble chocolate.
The head office of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the dignified Swiss private bank - it is only a little larger.
The situation is already classic.
The bank is headquartered on Zurich’s Bahnhofstraße, which leads directly from the central station to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-covered peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are splendid, the shop rentals are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers such as Tiffany’s can be found here between Swiss traditional shops such as the Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have lived here for centuries: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Bär.
You enter the reception hall of the UBS through a heavy turning door.
Inside, the walls are marble-clad, in front are thick leather armchairs, next to the bench logo a big sign for the "safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has been supplanted by both large Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but at some point – or betrayed, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, he does business with the two large banks, like all Swiss bankers.
The UBS has become much too large, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons would have also spread.
The Swiss have nothing more to say.
"And if they did, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was the Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed the UBS, first brought it high profits and then the debacle: No European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss big bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became visible.
"On Wednesday, the government coalition of the small seven-million-dollar country decided the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," author Lukas Hässig writes in his book The UBS Crash.
Up to 68 billion francs, or around 45 billion euros, were granted by the politicians to save the large bank that was facing bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem especially in the size of the UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three large Swiss banks merged into a huge group.
There was a bank that was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and it grew further and further.
The two different precursor banks of UBS complemented each other: a rich but sleepy bank with the focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer but already more internationalized bank.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers came in favor of a lot of money, with which they could turn a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, chief executive officer of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
“I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team,” says banking researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the high-intellectual, the modest, who understands a lot of models and statistics, and Ospel, the abdominal man who has worked from banking to the very top."
But Ospel finally relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: "He thought his models were the reality," Geiger says.
“This is a tragic case.”
Tragic, maybe.
It is clear that exuberance came before the case.
Employees at UBS clearly remember the executive meetings, at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly issued the same slogan: Goldman Sachs kicked off the throne.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the League Tables, the rankings that documented the success of the banks of that time.
The UBS wanted to go to the top.
Some steps had already succeeded.
She played at the top in foreign exchange and stock trading.
However, management consultants who were hired highlighted a weakness: in the international interest rate business, in the banking language "Fixed Income", there is a tremendous distance to the largest banks.
The UBS has gaps in American mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost it its existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund founded before it invested in American subprime assets.
It evolved into a huge machine that packaged and distributed securities on American mortgage loans, but also retained risks.
Even when other banks have long been looking for an exit.
“Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there,” said banking expert Geiger.
So great is the euphoria, so deep is the case.
One manager after another had to go away when the attempts to clean up were more difficult than thought.
Positions at UBS have become a centrifugal seat and are still shaky to this day.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He needs to find a strategy for a bank that has lost all the obvious business models.
Banking researcher Geiger already has an idea: stop investment banking, focus on asset management, return to the Swiss roots.
The bank does not (yet) want to go this far.
But investment banking is supposed to shrink sharply, so much is already clear.
Next Thursday, the new head of banking Sergio Ermotti wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a transitional solution when the bank surprisingly separated from its predecessor Grubel.
In the meantime, he has asserted himself: he should permanently manage the business of UBS, the Zurich Bank announced on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to bring the investment bank back to its level in the mid-1990s.
3500 marks.
But that won't be enough.
The UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
What does she want to make money with?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is surely asking himself now.
So far, he only says publicly that he and his wife will be looking for an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
