Intelligent crows spread in cities
In many places, crows are considered "problem birds": But the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts say.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities there are complaints from residents about dirt and noise from animals.
However, a remedy against the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows are no longer available from the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian Void.
There experts from all over the federal territory discussed possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Nature conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the land escape of the particularly protected seed crows: the use of chemicals in agriculture increasingly destroys the traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing cultivation and the falling of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected by nature.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs can be found in Westphalia’s Soest, in the northwest in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen as well as in Leer.
There in 2005 a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the county had provided negative headlines.
Critics had described catching the animals in bird traps and slaying them with sticks as particularly brutal.
"Normal expulsion, torment, brings nothing," said city and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer.
Sprinkling nests away with water or falling trees often have undesirable consequences, environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg said.
"The animals escape, large colonies split up and spread elsewhere."
Exceptions can only be made to hospitals, nursing homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away."
Without the surrounding area, the problem cannot be solved in the cities, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
It is conceivable a combination of torment of animals from sensitive living areas and attraction offers to resettle them in other places.
On the other hand, the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens advocated a completely different approach to the animals: "A pimple in the face can finally be tolerated best with confidence."
Jürgens had co-founded in Schleswig-Holstein the Asheberg Crow Teaching Path, on which signs inform about the life of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project is already being accepted by tourists.
Also on the criticism of the noise of the birds, Jürgens had his own opinion: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say to each other."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: crows not only use tools to get to a treat, but even make their own tools as tools.
Behavioral researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested four seed crows for how far the intelligence of birds reaches.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to use stones to bring down a scaffold in order to reach a moth larva.
Without much training, they determined what size and shape a stone must have in order to make the platform collapse.
In a second attempt, the clever crows had to solve a more tricky problem.
In a vertical cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak, the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had placed pieces of wire on them.
From this all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle from the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even succeeded in doing so at once.
