“We found it wasn’t hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopaedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply have to use the site’s advertising tool to accurately set their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy — just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with adds, but instead of connecting with a new band or a new diet product, the adds invited users to a survey asking about their educational status, their attitudes towards violence, and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without even having to leave their office once.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” Bartlett says.
Online sponsors of far-right groups are mostly young, male and annoyed by immigration.
But in a sort of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more sensible, more democratic and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three contents per day, Facebook’s “Data Supernova” is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers with the name of this page in the title by almost 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study people through this site that you don’t usually reach with your clipboard on the street.
“If you used to try to interview people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
"They had to inform the party first and they would never have granted them access," Bartlett said.
At Facebook, it all goes away – you go straight to them.”
Others say the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their full rush on Facebook are significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who are silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that peer students, such as residential consultants, monitor the site and help a student if it posts too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you haven’t realized it,” Dimitri Christakis, Moreno’s co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, told the Washington Post.
“We’ve found a way to identify vulnerable children that wouldn’t have been found otherwise.”
Facebook is also constantly hacking the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using data that only Facebook has access to – digital freedom masters have long known that the site should make their large data mine accessible for other research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not, and in order to be able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to share its own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have thought at all about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study in which he examined students’ public pages on Facebook.
"As for her, it was just about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how many of the information in a user profile and in posts are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn said.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and pencil are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
"Social research has to take care of the social - and a lot of social life is still taking place offline."
