7 Lessons From The Interview With The Deceased Steve Jobs Shown At A Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the engineering genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans may find most insightful in the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted this week before special film screenings in the major markets, is how much this creative head has understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and a self-appointed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer, eager to craft charts - a man who believed that many executives suffer from "a disease of thought," "that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there's a tremendous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great one."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Idiots" about the break-up of the personal computer, and he spent more than an hour working on one of the rare, in-depth conversations.
By that time, it had been like 10 years since Jobs had been pushed out of Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, looking forward to the widespread adoption of the internet.
While a small part of Cringley’s interview was used in specialist idiots, he says that the copy templates of the interview were missing at delivery.
It was only after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which comes to the Landmark Theatre this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating detailed interviews, Jobs appears surprisingly zealous in explaining his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four longer pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of meditation, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatiently responds to Cringely’s questions and urges him to respond more quickly to more important topics or side actions.
Before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone recorded, the Lost Interview seems somehow eerily far-sighted when Jobs assesses what other companies are doing right or wrong in his opinion and represents his own vision for the future of the computer.
It’s one thing to read posthumous appreciations of Career Jobs, but to see Jobs here as the eager dreamer on the leap to grandeur is something quite different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this here, he left and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a company:
"Throughout the years in business, I always ask, 'Why are you doing things?' And the answer you always get is, 'Oh, that's how it's made easy.'
No one knows why he does what he does. No one in business really thinks deeply about things.
That's what I found out.
Jobs is continuing its efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Amazed at how costs were recorded - usually starting with "standard costs", which were calculated on the basis of mere assumption and then adjusted with "deviation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined down to the smallest.
How the Pope was dismissed:
Jobs tells of the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device with which you could sneak into the telephone company and lead long distance conversations for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs’ enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the boxes by using a paid phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while scrolling through as many satellites as possible.
“We sent things around the globe half a dozen times, and when you go on the phone, it came out a minute later on the phone next door,” Jobs says with a whisper.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don’t think there would be Apple without it.
Jobs continues to tell of a glorious prank that Wozniak and he nearly pulled off when they called in the middle of the night via the Blue Box in the Vatican and wanted to talk to the Pope while they were able to imitate Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope himself answered the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and unpreparedly called Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, when he was searching for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"It had a remarkable impact on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small screen with a brown tube and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for it.
How to improve innovations:
Several times in the interview Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he installed some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the entire computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and the delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he remembers the problems he had in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember punctuating arguments ... they screamed at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer.”
Ninety days later we had a mouse that we were able to build for $15. That was incredibly credible.
About large companies that are slowing down:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their shares.
“Let’s say you’re working at IBM or Xerox, so you’re making a better copier or printer, well what?”
They own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [it’s such people] who ultimately run the companies and the product that pushes people out of decision making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is eradicated by people who have no concept regarding good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship necessary.
This happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger, Microsoft could have been the 1990s...
They have lost the victory.
About innovation as an art form:
“There’s a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about his subtleties.
You have to make votes, certain things you can't, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5,000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
Ultimately, it comes down to taste, it comes down to trying to deal with the best stuff that humans have created, and then trying to bring these things together into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who were randomly the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren’t for the computer industry, they would create fantastic things in other areas.
