How to Disguise a Lie
A look at the current headlines shows how troubling and widespread deception and lying are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy dealing with accusations of sexual harassment by several women, both sides accuse each other of lying.
Penn State's leadership is accused of perjury, allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was listened to when French President Nikolas Sarkozy told US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign funding violations related to cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied during his second term in the Oval Office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories about cheating in school and at college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents where teachers have given their students the exam responses so that they can stand well on their own performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times every day.
But many of these lies are considered to be necessities.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or "discovering lies" is one that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game like Sharaden, in which the goal is to call "Haw Yourself!", uncovering a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out far-reaching research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most ancient myths about lying have been uncovered.
Lies look into one's eyes.
They don’t always stotter, stem, blush, and twitch.
However, it should not be concluded from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and uncover.
A trained liar can penetrate to the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the extensive and steadily growing field of disguise, and it is clear that disguising a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to find out in our complex world, especially when hiring or consulting people or negotiating or administering belongs to our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at assessing other people, arousing their interest and mastering their own emotions. And they intuitively feel how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people that men are more likely to "self-oriented" lies than women whose lies are more "orientated to others" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat").
We also know that when a person has been exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluating changes.
Observe the attitude, the laughter, the vocal quality of your subject.
They should know better when someone usually tripped their foot constantly, so they don’t blame them wrongly if they tripped their foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that are screaming, not as evidence of disguise.
People who deceive may get frozen when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet point toward the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relaxation after the interview", that deep, relaxing exhalation and change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Askers often incorrectly signal that a job interview is over, only to look for this relaxation after the job interview.
Also, pay attention to the language of your experimenter.
Scott Peterson's slipper is famous when he used the past form when he claimed that his murdered wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceiving people can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have a sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or when you repeat a tricky question overall.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than factual, which often causes the alarm bells to ring.
There is no magic to uncover lies, but you can learn skills thanks to which uncovering is possible.
Thanks to these skills, anyone can less often become a victim of fraudsters, both in private and professional life.
