Climate Opportunities Brake the Economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and black labour rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the initiator of change and raised great hopes for economic growth, is in the government. However, as a result of climatic adversities, growth cannot be talked about, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators have deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of losses in agriculture, but also placed tight limits on the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6% in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development of 31.16%, which had a slowing effect on other economic sectors.
According to a report by the Mexican Council for Rural Sustainability on the effects of the frost, 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, 78.03 percent of which was completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has steadily increased unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografia observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, because from January to March 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53% of the working population. In the second quarter the unemployment rate rose to 74 percent in the first quarter, from September to September to September.
Lower liquidity
The economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autonoma (UAS), comments that the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
“What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with a number of factors, including liquidity losses in the market as a result of the cuts in money laundering legislation passed in Congress, because for those who are prohibited to accumulate dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else,” he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also inherent in a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined. This is due on the one hand to the problems of entry and on the other because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and are looking for work here, which increases unemployment," he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, considering the high proportion of black labour, which, according to INEGI, encompasses 60.38 percent of workers in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and black labour are the lowest wages in Mexico, according to statistics from the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexico Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Mexico’s government agency for labour and social welfare).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos up to September, which is much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADI
In addition to declining economic activity and rising unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years was recorded in 2011. According to the Secretaria de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI amounted to $ 630,597 from January to June, representing a decline of 87.74 percent compared to $ 5,143,312 in the same period last year.
The Secretaria de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Governmental Authority for Economic Development) for its part recorded a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debts
In the face of the economic crisis, the state government applied in July to the National Congress for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The state Congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive effects of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be detected by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdés’s inability to govern obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (Mexico’s state chamber of manufacturing industry), said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonize the views of different sectors, including the state government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. Hard work has to be done to regain the ground lost this year and in 2012 we have to do twice. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well-coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently aligned," he explained.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said events such as the frost at the beginning of the year hampered and slowed the country’s economic development.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the main impacts is a slowing economy that is not sufficiently moving to create an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services, so we will close the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining the Call
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana in Sinaloa, said that the state must be encouraged to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to re-establish the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources Sinaloa," he said.
There's a lot to do
The president of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will steer the government’s efforts in better ways.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he explained.
He stressed that the current state power has made progress in the government.
“There are areas where you can say that the government has acted more comprehensively, what I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it,” he said.
