The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium from 7.30 p.m. together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
They read an excerpt from the conversation, the full copy of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: do you realize what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that comes true for us as well.
This is just the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica once for a holiday. It is such a beautiful country that we will definitely stay there for a few more days.
It’s exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you because the fans of the band are totally devoted, they experience the days before the concert intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for standing by our side all these years.
It took us nearly 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we’re sorry it took us so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Isn't that a little bit of pressure from your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve put on in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played at some giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing and are delighted with the jungle, which is why Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone to Costa Rica and Nicaragua for surfing. Together with Mexico, these are excellent surfing areas. In this way, we learned about people who love surfing.
With a look at the tour you have offered giant shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there, we do not set any limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with a lot of different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why did you?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Each one likes a different song, so the decision we’re going to play isn’t easy.
If we add two or three songs to the repertoire that we haven’t played for a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think that’s why it’s also interesting for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, is it hard for you to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I think none of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years, and that sounds like a dream.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like ourselves and are thrilled to produce music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to the places of the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to have participated actively in the birth of Grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of big bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Occasionally a band emerges from a city, but it is unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are happy to still be friends with them all and we are honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It’s also very unusual for a band like yours to have stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. That alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we all appreciate ourselves lucky to be still alive and also take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and their music. We couldn't be better.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy; on the other hand, thanks to your success, you have always been able to do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find balance.
We make sure you don’t go on tour too often, because it’s too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came in because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what you created it without being a famous rock star.
What are your memories of Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years who had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed that it took us so long. We’re still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built the band with us. When I listen to a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It’s always been a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and soccer.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her works, especially Eddie Vedder, and that is why you chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several bands and we liked this band best, so we are curious to see what Las Robertas live has to offer. That will surely be exciting.
Why do you always change the text of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That's a question for Eddie Vedder, I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing he can think of.
Who were you influenced by as a bassist?
by so many+
Among the first to think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I liked.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive even though it’s no longer a fad?
I think we all don’t feel very attached to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I remember the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else who came up at the same time. If they still matter today, I think that’s great because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney now make better music than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now she is more positive.
Why did you?
That’s interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might look a little light-hearted, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about themselves.
The tears came to me when I heard Ed playing them. It's very dark songs.
I think as you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life—for example, when you lose a family member or a friend—that affects your artistic creation and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also think that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
