Fujimori returned to the hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to examine the muscle loss of his legs, his family doctor informed.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990-2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which is operated on and under control four times.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga and his personal doctor told TV that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but he did not want it because he considered him innocent.
He has been operated on four times for tongue cancer and has lost 18 kilos of weight, along with other conditions such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulation problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been held in the National Directorate of Special Operations of the Police since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which was working secretly during his time in government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will begin its visit from Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues of the region.
Mujica meets with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón on Wednesday, which, according to the Uruguayan president, will be the culmination of his full schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón’s support in the incident with France when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy placed the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still act as tax havens from the international community. This declaration was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request to his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group of the world’s most powerful emerging and industrialized countries, and since January of this year there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to accelerate the concreteization of agreements on the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "gray list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not introduced all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
At the commercial level, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
