Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organization was created to avoid the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the social welfare organization Trinijove have led to important results: in this quarter century, 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion were supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are more than a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary yesterday, an event in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which more than 300 people participated, was taken into account.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems threatened by the risk of marginality.
Yesterday’s celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by many leaders of institutions and institutions that have worked with the association during these 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different directions during the election season demonstrated the impartiality of Trinijove’s work.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol participated in the celebrations of the former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and currently left-green city councilman Ricard Goma.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the General Director of the Social Work of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was launched in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but he added that the work so far done "is a good foundation".
For the president of the Generalitat, Trinijove is an example that knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
“The economic crisis is nothing new for the association and the work it does,” he said.
Occupied house where giant parties were held was cleared
The homeowners occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on Balmes Street No. 51 (Barcelona).
The 12 occupiers left the building yesterday afternoon without any resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of House No. 51 have come to an end on Balmes Street.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building, which they had illegally occupied at noon, and in which they had organized huge festivals that had driven the neighborhood to despair. The eviction was carried out on a court order without police intervention.
After the eviction, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be checked," the house manager confirmed.
The occupants, who occupied 11 of the 13 apartments of the building - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply, and painted the walls and left all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
In the three lower floors, huge parties were celebrated, which lasted up to two days and drove the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also carried damage from it.
Her owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business would have declined by 80% since the start of the occupancy.
The owner of the disco pointed out that the house occupants were competing unfairly because they sold the drinks for three euros, while they cost 10 euros in the disco.
In addition, the owner of the recreational venue had been notified by the neighbors for rest disturbance, while according to her statement the noise did not come from the visitors to the disco, but from the occupiers and especially from the guests of the festivals that were organized there, which according to the angry neighbors became more and more longer in the last weeks.
The managers of the disco explained that the harassment had been so great that they agreed with the owner of the building not to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (city police) also confirmed that it had received more complaints from neighbors in recent weeks.
The chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in Barcelona's city council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, last week called for the building to be evacuated immediately and to deal with the problems of civic coexistence and the coming down of the neighborhood.
He explained that before the summer, only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that in recent months the occupiers had entered all floors of the building and almost all apartments.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to crack down on the asocial actions in the building."
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris district was cleared by the Catalan police.
At 3.30 p.m., police approached Montral Street No. 35 after receiving a call from a neighbor who had watched four people trying to break into the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
