The tender for the 16 gates opens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the disappeared Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its reproach on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It was even compared in numbers to New York’s Central Park.
With the collapse of the CMB in 1987, in the eyes of many, the park became once again the upper limit of Barcelona, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not spread in the north-south direction, but upwards (mountains) and downwards (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park plays with this idea.
The role model was now not Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars in the role of the Yogi Bear.
This was the case when the city issued a huge tender in September, consisting of 16 competitions, for further gateways to Collserola.
Undoubtedly, a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either that's the way it is, or someone's planning on putting goals on the land.
The question of itself: Collserola, park or mountain?
The invitation to tender is not only from an organizational point of view, but also in view of a reflection on the city the topic of discussion in the mouth of all architects from Barcelona.
It is almost a recurring theme to which two members of this old caste, who meet in the elevator, can resort.
And precisely this fact provides the fabric for one of the rare matches between what three architects from Barcelona think about it and some university professors who have applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Roldán "it is necessary" to speak about the "front on the mountain" after the attack on the coast, insofar as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, which has not been held about the green apples.
“It should be assumed that Barcelona’s biggest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex," says the architect, for whom the title "Gates of Collserola" carries a "lexical trap": one must not imagine it "as access to a park, but as a delimitation of areas where action must be taken."
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with urban development experience, regards the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" that carries "some dangers".
Dangers as a result of the "uncertainty associated with the design of a public space today" according to the experiences of the 1980s, which had their "swan singing" in the area of the forum.
The first fear is its own limitation on what can be cultivated.
“Constricting something always means defining the next step,” i.e. exceeding it.
