Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome announced details of the plane crash in which government Secretary Francisco Blake and seven others were killed.
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport - SCT (Secretariat of Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation of the accident in which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people were killed indicate that the helicopter with its entire intact structure crashed directly into the ground without the pilot having been able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before launch that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wing had contact with trees at 25 meters altitude, with the helicopter losing the hull, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for the transport of personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the aircraft had crashed.
"In the search, no aircraft parts were found elsewhere, the impact affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has an inclination of 7 to 30 degrees.
Currently, it is a priority to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but these could take several months, perhaps even a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, General Director of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter had flown from the Presidential State Mayor at a speed of travel and that the plane had fallen to a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the collision."
During a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, noted six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visible flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of the visual flight, which means that the crew should have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at take-off, with some low-hanging clouds picking up during the flight to the Mexico City-Mexico border area.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Impact point:
The impact coordinates and the helicopter's last radar record match. There may have been no loss of control over the aircraft or deviation from the flight route before the impact.
Dispersal of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date suggests that the helicopter was impacted from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter with its intact structure had impacted the ground.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft do not indicate fire or explosion at the site of the accident.
The latest results suggest several ground contacts.
In the field investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is sloping and has an inclination of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter was likely to have broken.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a thorough search of an area beyond the locked area at the accident site, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, further reinforcing the assumption that the intact aircraft structure had crashed into the ground.
MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
The Social Security Agency of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by specialists of the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Agency of Mexico) announced that it is conducting a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence" to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI Clinic, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers has been set up.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate program at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) of the Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested participants can come to the sports grounds of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where every Saturday from 8.00 am tests are carried out with children and adolescents.
He stressed that the investigation began at the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of Mexico) and will continue since October 8 at the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of Mexico).
If the target of 500 to 600 investigators is reached, the study will be continued at the Independencia sports ground (in the south of the capital district) and completed at the Morelos sports ground (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study is to learn about the factors and role of genetics associated with the development of obesity and identify risk factors for Mexican children and adolescents to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the World Diabetes Day, he said that the aim was for three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 to complete nutritional questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and family history of disease to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He further stated that on those Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, height, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood levels such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (trying to identify genes related to obesity in childhood) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be carried out on the occasion of the concern of health personnel about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in nearly six years the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico differs from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average Mexican is 65 percent Indian-American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity is expressed in the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) taken to us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the subjects would be a comprehensive study of the children, in which it would be determined whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even examine the occurrence of dark skin wrinkles in the neck and inner arm (akanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the pre-stage.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors will explain to the parents all measurement results and suggest to them lifestyle changes that are appropriate to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors responsible for obesity, obesity, and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV, and using means of transportation, instead of walking short distances.
