If the signs emanating from the road surfaces were considerably taken into consideration, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 puncture holes if the rainy season erupted in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, warning and assuring the number of the punctures that if the
In his lecture "Batholes from a Technical Perspective", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road coverings and thus avoid the appearance of punctures.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, some of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together they give the road surface its characteristic elastic behavior.
The tensile-elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C., at 120° C. it is very viscous and almost solid at 50° C., while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City have mostly a flexible road surface that is composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones, made of asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "a last layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which has also been bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
This road surface receives and distributes the most forces, the support layer also needs an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water, "he said, because it significantly impairs the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain gets moist, water penetrates into the layer and is difficult to get out, causing all layers of road surfaces to soften and, as a result, the appearance of puncture holes.
When a punch hole is created, the top layer is first removed, while the wear layer is not damaged until afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the appearance of striking holes, so the thickness of each layer of road covering must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with to avoid frequent striking holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, such as asphalt emulsions that are already on the market in other countries, and with which the puncture holes could be repaired easily and without applying high temperatures.
