Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas transmission line, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is expected to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with brilliance and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas line, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level, on Tuesday at the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sound and at the gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his counterpart Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically jointly turned the control of the valve that transports Russian gas to the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gases are to be delivered to Western Europe each year through a first pipeline of 1,224 km length connecting the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total delivery of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of French total consumption - is to be completed by the end of 2012.
And the eventuality of the construction of a third line on the same route is already announced.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will enable direct gas delivery to Germany, avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little bit of their power: it will now become more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not shy from comparing the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive at first.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of de-energizing European energy, as the project has broken a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In barely five years, Russia has achieved its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, which have high gas consumption and whose gas reserves are on the decline.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which large gas contracts are also important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the Gazprom managers, who are numerous in Lubmin, regarding gas supply.
The construction of this gas transmission line is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel with concrete sheathing, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the sea floor, at about 200 m depth.
During its construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be evaded.
“About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precautionary measure,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for the company Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which is interrupted over the entire length by nothing: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers distanced themselves from it, as the Swedes were little keen to see a Russian state-owned company permanently settle at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of a disaster, we will close the gas passage in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the case of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers to be unlikely, since the suede seams were estimated to be at a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation by a seagoing vessel and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, has a diameter of one meter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and is moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas transmission line was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (each 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each 9%).
These five companies have formed a business community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company on a renewable 20-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how much gas it actually transports," Jens Müller said.
The financing of gas transmission construction was covered by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs are expected to amount to €7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the total investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are willing to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline comes to light on a sandy, pine-wooded coastline near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other key figures of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas transmission lines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
